ares boot attempt — task 20.4b / 20.4c evidence
================================================

STATUS 2026-07-23 (updated after xorg-server-xvfb was installed)

RESOLVED: the earlier "ares exits with SIGSEGV before producing any output"
finding was purely a missing X display. With xvfb present, ares starts
normally and runs the ROM for the full timeout without crashing:

    $ xvfb-run -a ares --system "Nintendo 64" --no-file-prompt n64-doom.z64
    OpenGL Version: 4.6 (Core Profile) Mesa 26.1.5-arch3.1, GLSL: 4.60
    OpenGL: Failed to load librashader: shaders will be disabled
    (runs until the 25 s timeout; exit 124 = still running, not a crash)

The librashader line is cosmetic — an optional shader library, not required.

CURRENT BLOCKER: the ROM contains no WAD, by construction.

    tools/n64/n64_main.c:52   n64_register_wad(NULL, 0);

and the ROM packing step appends only the stripped ELF:

    n64tool --title "webdoom-n64" --output n64-doom.z64 --align 256 \
            n64-doom.elf.stripped

Confirmed empirically — the 360,448-byte ROM contains no IWAD/PWAD magic:

    $ grep -c "IWAD\|PWAD" n64-doom.z64
    0

So D_DoomMain cannot reach its banner: there is no WAD to identify or load.
This ROM is a *footprint-measurement artifact* (see docs/n64/BRING-UP.md §2),
not a playable build, and no emulator configuration changes that.

WHY THERE IS NO ISVIEWER OUTPUT
ares does implement the ISViewer debug channel that libdragon's
debug_init(DEBUG_FEATURE_LOG_EMU) writes to:

    ares/n64/cartridge/cartridge.cpp:52-54
        isviewer.tracer = node->append<Node::Debugger::Tracer::Notification>(...)
        isviewer.tracer->setTerminal(true);

and Notification::notify() gates on enabled(), which is `file() || terminal()`
(ares/node/debugger/tracer/tracer.hpp:9). Because setTerminal(true) is applied
at construction, ISViewer text WOULD reach the terminal. The absence of output
is therefore evidence about the ROM, not about ares configuration: execution
never reaches a debugf() call, which is consistent with a NULL WAD.

WHAT A BOOTABLE ROM REQUIRES (next task)
 1. Embed an IWAD in the ROM image (n64tool can append data after the ELF) and
    pass its cartridge address to n64_register_wad() instead of NULL.
 2. Decide WAD residency: the smallest IWAD available here is doom.wad at
    12,408,292 B. N64 cartridges reach 64 MB so ROM size is not the issue, but
    RDRAM is 4 MB — the WAD must be read in place from cartridge address space
    rather than copied into RAM. files_n64.c already takes a pointer+length, so
    the work is in where that pointer points and how reads are serviced.
 3. Re-run `make boot-log` and expect a D_DoomMain banner over ISViewer.

REPRODUCTION
    source ~/toolchains/env.sh
    cd tools/n64 && make all
    make boot-log ARES=$HOME/toolchains/bin/ares ARES_TIMEOUT=25

Pass ARES explicitly, or ensure ~/toolchains/bin is on PATH: xvfb-run does not
inherit a PATH that was set only inside the make invocation. Raw capture from
each run is written to ares-boot-raw.log; this file is curated evidence.
